---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const draft = true; // STAGED: remove this line on publish date
const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does 'under contract' mean in Brisbane real estate?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under contract means the property has an executed contract of sale: both buyer and seller have signed. However, the sale has not yet completed (settled). The property may still be subject to conditions such as finance approval or building and pest inspection. It becomes sold when settlement occurs and title transfers."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between conditional and unconditional under contract in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A conditional contract has outstanding conditions that must be satisfied before the sale is legally binding on both parties. Common conditions include finance approval, building and pest inspection, and due diligence. An unconditional contract has no remaining conditions: both parties are legally committed to complete the sale and neither can withdraw without consequences."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a seller accept another offer while the property is under contract?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A seller can receive and consider backup offers while a property is under contract, but cannot execute a second contract while the first contract is live. If the first contract falls through during the conditional period, the seller can move to a backup buyer. Speak to your solicitor before making any commitments to backup buyers."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout title="What 'Under Contract' Means in Brisbane Real Estate: A Seller's Guide | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Under contract, conditional, unconditional, backup offer: what these terms mean in Queensland and what sellers should do at each stage of the process." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)}></script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        ← All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What 'Under Contract' Means in Brisbane Real Estate: A Seller's Guide to Contract Status
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Going under contract is a major milestone in a sale campaign, but it is not the finish line. Here is what the different contract statuses actually mean in Queensland, what your obligations are at each stage, and when a sale becomes final.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>After weeks of open homes, negotiations, and buyer follow-up, your agent calls to say you are under contract. For most sellers, this is an enormous relief. The campaign has worked. A buyer has committed. But going under contract in Queensland is not the same as completing the sale, and understanding exactly where you are in the process matters for the decisions you make from that point until settlement day.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What 'under contract' means</h2>
      <p>A property is under contract when both buyer and seller have signed the contract of sale. Exchange has occurred. There is a legally binding agreement in place, but the sale is not yet complete because completion (settlement) has not happened. Settlement is the date on which the buyer pays the balance of the purchase price, the seller hands over vacant possession, and the title to the property transfers from the seller's name to the buyer's name.</p>

      <p>Between exchange and settlement, the property is neither fully yours nor fully theirs. You remain the legal owner, but you are bound by the terms of the contract and cannot simply withdraw or sell to someone else. The buyer cannot take possession or use the property until settlement occurs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Conditional versus unconditional</h2>
      <p>Most contracts in Queensland are entered into with conditions attached. The most common conditions are finance approval, building and pest inspection, and sometimes due diligence or body corporate search for units and townhouses. While these conditions are outstanding, the contract is conditional.</p>

      <p>A conditional contract means the sale is not yet certain. Either party may be entitled to terminate the contract if a condition is not satisfied by the agreed date. If the buyer's finance is not approved, or if the building and pest inspection reveals issues that the parties cannot agree to deal with, the buyer may have the right to walk away and have their deposit refunded. This is why going under contract, while a very positive development, is not a cause for complete certainty until the conditions have been satisfied.</p>

      <p>When all conditions have been satisfied or waived, the contract becomes unconditional. At that point, both parties are legally committed to completing the sale. An unconditional contract can still fall over in rare circumstances, but the consequences for the party who fails to complete are significant: forfeiture of deposit and potential claim for damages. In practice, an unconditional contract settling is very close to a certainty.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When listing portals show 'under contract'</h2>
      <p>Realestate.com.au and Domain.com.au allow agents to flag a property as under contract after exchange. In practice, agents vary in when they update this status: some do it immediately after signing, others wait until the contract goes unconditional, and some leave it until settlement is confirmed. If you are searching the portals and see a property listed as under contract, you can contact the agent to find out whether there is still an opportunity to register interest as a backup buyer.</p>

      <p>As the seller, your agent should update the listing status promptly after exchange. Leaving it showing as active after you have gone under contract creates unnecessary work for agents and confusion for buyers who enquire.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Can another buyer make an offer while you are under contract?</h2>
      <p>Technically yes, you can receive and consider backup offers while a property is under contract. You cannot, however, execute a second contract while the first contract is live. Executing two contracts simultaneously on the same property would create serious legal complications and your solicitor would not permit it.</p>

      <p>What you can do is maintain contact with a buyer who has expressed strong interest as a backup, so that if the first contract falls through during the conditional period, you can move quickly to the backup buyer without relaunching the campaign. Whether this is worth doing depends on the circumstances: how conditional the first contract is, how long the condition period runs, and how genuine the backup buyer's interest appears to be.</p>

      <p>Get advice from your solicitor before making any commitments or representations to a backup buyer. There are constraints on what you can say and do while a contract is on foot, and the last thing you want is to create a situation where both buyers believe they have a commitment from you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The cooling-off period</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, buyers purchasing residential property by private treaty (not at auction) have a statutory cooling-off period of five business days from the date of contract. During this period, the buyer can terminate the contract and receive their deposit back, less a 0.25% termination penalty of the purchase price. Properties sold at auction do not have a cooling-off period.</p>

      <p>As the seller, you do not have a cooling-off right. Once you have signed a contract and delivered it to the buyer (or their solicitor), the contract is binding on you. This is worth understanding before you sign, because changing your mind after exchange is not as straightforward as it might be for the buyer during the cooling-off window.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do while under contract</h2>
      <p>Continue to maintain the property in the same condition as it was at the time of exchange. The buyer has the right to a pre-settlement inspection (typically in the 24 to 48 hours before settlement) to confirm the property is in the condition described in the contract and that all inclusions are present. If the property has deteriorated, or if items listed as inclusions have been removed, the buyer can raise an objection and delay settlement.</p>

      <p>Do not disconnect utilities until after settlement. Do not remove fixtures or fittings that were present at the time of inspection unless you have explicitly disclosed and agreed in the contract that they would be removed. Do not allow the property to fall into disrepair, leave significant rubbish on site, or take any action that would materially change the condition of the property from what the buyer inspected.</p>

      <p>Keep in regular contact with your solicitor during the condition period. Your solicitor will notify you of condition satisfaction dates, request any documents needed for settlement, and manage the transfer of title. If conditions are not satisfied on time or a dispute arises, your solicitor needs to be across the situation immediately.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When 'under contract' becomes 'sold'</h2>
      <p>The property is sold when settlement occurs. At settlement, the buyer pays the balance of the purchase price (the full purchase price less their deposit, which is usually held in a trust account by the real estate agent or solicitor). The seller's mortgage, if any, is discharged. Title to the property transfers from the seller to the buyer in the Queensland land title register. Keys are handed over.</p>

      <p>From that point, the property belongs to the buyer. The listing portals are updated to show sold. The agent's commission is released from trust. And you, as the seller, have completed the transaction.</p>

      <p>The period between going under contract and reaching settlement is typically four to six weeks in Queensland, though shorter and longer settlement periods are common depending on what was negotiated. If you are purchasing another property simultaneously, the settlement dates on your sale and your purchase need to be coordinated. Your solicitor and your finance broker should be working together on this from the time your sale goes unconditional.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
